# Conventional Commits Format
# ===========================
# <type>[optional scope]: <description>
#
# [optional body]
#
# [optional footer: BREAKING CHANGE: <description>]
#
# Valid Types:
#   feat:     New feature for the user
#   fix:      Bug fix for the user
#   docs:     Documentation only changes
#   style:    Code style changes (formatting, semicolons, etc)
#   refactor: Code refactoring (neither fixes bug nor adds feature)
#   perf:     Performance improvements
#   test:     Adding or updating tests
#   build:    Build system or external dependencies
#   ci:       CI/CD pipeline changes
#   chore:    Maintenance tasks, version bumps, etc
#   revert:   Reverts a previous commit
#
# Examples:
#   feat(casino): implement gold-based gambling mechanics
#   fix(room_casino): prevent creatures from breaking walls
#   docs: update FORK_WORKFLOW.md with versioning info
#
# Breaking Changes (triggers MAJOR version bump):
#   feat(api): remove deprecated room_model field
#   
#   BREAKING CHANGE: room_model field removed from API.
#   Use room_kind field instead.
#
# Scope Guidelines:
#   - Use component/module name: (casino), (creature), (frontend)
#   - Keep lowercase, no spaces
#   - Optional but recommended for clarity
#
# Description Guidelines:
#   - Use imperative mood: "add" not "added" or "adds"
#   - Don't capitalize first letter
#   - No period at the end
#   - Minimum 10 characters
#
# Body Guidelines (optional):
#   - Separate from description with blank line
#   - Explain what and why, not how
#   - Wrap at 72 characters
#
# Footer Guidelines (optional):
#   - Separate from body with blank line
#   - Use for breaking changes, issue references
#   - Format: "BREAKING CHANGE: <description>"
#   - Format: "Fixes #123" or "Closes #456"
#
# Note: The commit hook will validate this format
# Note: -Cerwym fork identifier is automatically added to version strings
